GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 358
Short Title: Maintain NAIC Accreditation of DOI.-AB (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Humphrey.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Insurance, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of
the House
March 12, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAINTAIN NAIC ACCREDITATION OF THE DEPARTMENT OF
3 INSURANCE BY IMPLEMENTING GROUP CAPITAL CALCULATION AND
4 LIQUIDITY STRESS TEST REQUIREMENTS AND TO MAKE VARIOUS
5 CONFORMING CHANGES, AS RECOMMENDED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF
6 INSURANCE.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. IMPLEMENT GROUP CAPITAL CALCULATION AND LIQUIDITY STRESS
10 TEST REQUIREMENTS FOR INSURANCE HOLDING COMPANY SYSTEMS
11 SECTION 1. Article 19 of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
12 the following new sections to read:
13 "§ 58-19-26. Group capital calculation.
14 (a) Reporting Requirement. – The ultimate controlling person of every insurer subject to
15 registration pursuant to G.S. 58-19-25 shall concurrently file with the registration an annual
16 group capital calculation report. The report shall be filed with the lead state commissioner.
17 (b) Exemptions. – The ultimate controlling person of any of the following is exempt from
18 the filing requirement of subsection (a) of this section:
19 (1) An insurance holding company system that (i) has only one insurer within its
20 holding company structure, (ii) only writes insurance business, (iii) is only
21 licensed in its state of domicile, and (iv) assumes no business from any other
22 insurer.
23 (2) An insurance holding company system that is required to perform a group
24 capital calculation specified by the United States Federal Reserve Board.
25 When this exemption applies, the lead state commissioner shall request the
26 calculation from the United States Federal Reserve Board. If the United States
27 Federal Reserve Board cannot share the calculation with the lead state
28 commissioner under the terms of any information sharing agreements in
29 effect, then the insurance holding company system is not exempt from the
30 group capital calculation filing.
31 (3) An insurance holding company system whose non-United States group-wide
32 supervisor is located within a reciprocal jurisdiction that recognizes the United
33 States state regulatory approach to group supervision and group capital.
*H358-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) An insurance holding company system that meets both of the following
2 requirements:
3 a. The insurance holding company system provides information to the
4 lead state commissioner that meets the requirements for accreditation
5 under the NAIC financial standards and accreditation program. The
6 insurance holding company may provide this information either
7 directly or indirectly through its group-wide supervisor. If provided
8 indirectly through a group-wide supervisor, the supervisor is
9 responsible for determining whether the information provided is
10 sufficient to permit the lead state commissioner to comply with the
11 NAIC group supervision approach, as detailed in the NAIC Financial
12 Analysis Handbook.
13 b. The insurance holding company system's non-United States
14 group-wide supervisor is not in a reciprocal jurisdiction but
15 nonetheless recognizes the group capital calculation as the worldwide
16 group capital assessment for United States insurance groups who
17 operate in that jurisdiction.
18 (c) Recognition of Group Capital Calculation. – For purposes of subdivision (b)(4) of
19 this section, a non-United States jurisdiction recognizes the group capital calculation if it satisfies
20 any of the following criteria:
21 (1) A competent regulatory authority in the jurisdiction affirms that insurers and
22 insurance groups whose lead state is accredited by the NAIC under the NAIC
23 accreditation program shall be subject only to worldwide prudential insurance
24 group supervision, including worldwide group governance, solvency and
25 capital, and reporting, as applicable, by that jurisdiction's lead state
26 commissioner and will not be subject to group supervision, including
27 worldwide group governance, solvency and capital, and reporting, at the level
28 of the worldwide parent undertaking of the insurance or reinsurance group by
29 the non-United States jurisdiction.
30 (2) A competent regulatory authority in the jurisdiction affirms that information
31 regarding insurers and their parent, subsidiary, or affiliated entities, if
32 applicable, shall be provided to the lead state commissioner in accordance
33 with an information sharing agreement in the form of a memorandum of
34 understanding or similar document. Acceptable information sharing
35 agreements include the International Association of Insurance Supervisors
36 Multilateral Memorandum of Understanding or other multilateral memoranda
37 of understanding coordinated by the NAIC. The jurisdiction does not satisfy
38 this criteria if the lead state commissioner determines, in consultation with the
39 NAIC, that the requirements of the information sharing agreements are no
40 longer in force.
41 (3) If no United States insurance groups operate in the non-United States
42 jurisdiction, that non-United States jurisdiction notifies the lead state
43 commissioner and the International Association of Insurance Supervisors in
44 writing that the jurisdiction considers the group capital calculation an
45 acceptable international capital standard.
46 (d) Limitation of Exemptions. – Notwithstanding subsection (b) of this section, the lead
47 state commissioner shall require filing of the group capital calculation for United States
48 operations of any non-United States based insurance holding company system if the lead state
49 commissioner determines that the filing is required for (i) prudential oversight and solvency
50 monitoring purposes or (ii) ensuring the competitiveness of the insurance marketplace.
Page 2 House Bill 358-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) Consideration and Correction of NAIC Materials. – The lead state commissioner shall
2 consider any relevant lists, reports, and recommendations published by the NAIC in determining
3 whether the exceptions of subdivision (b)(4) of this section apply to an insurer. If the lead state
4 commissioner's determination differs from relevant materials published by the NAIC, the lead
5 state commissioner shall provide the NAIC with written justification for the difference supported
6 by documentation. If published NAIC materials indicate that a non-United States jurisdiction
7 recognizes the group capital calculation and the lead state commissioner determines that the
8 jurisdiction no longer meets the requirements of subsection (c) of this section, the lead state
9 commissioner may recommend a correction of the materials to the NAIC.
10 (f) Discretionary Exemptions. – The lead state commissioner may either (i) exempt the
11 ultimate controlling person of an insurance holding company system from the filing requirement
12 of subsection (a) of this section or (ii) authorize the ultimate controlling person of an insurance
13 holding company to file a limited group capital filing in lieu of the filing requirement of
14 subsection (a) of this section if all of the following apply:
15 (1) The insurance holding company system has annual direct written and
16 unaffiliated assumed premium, including international direct and assumed
17 premium, but excluding premiums reinsured with the Federal Crop Insurance
18 Corporation and Federal Flood Program, of less than one billion dollars
19 ($1,000,000,000).
20 (2) The insurance holding company system does not include insurers within its
21 holding company structure that are domiciled outside of the United States or
22 one of its territories.
23 (3) The insurance holding company system does not include banking, depository,
24 or other financial entity that is subject to an identified regulatory capital
25 framework within its holding company structure.
26 (4) The insurance holding company system attests that there are no material
27 changes in transactions between insurers and non-insurers in the group that
28 have occurred since the last filing of an annual group calculation report, if any.
29 (5) The non-insurers within the insurance holding company system do not pose a
30 material financial risk to the insurer's ability to honor policyholder
31 obligations.
32 (g) Resumption of Filings. – If the lead state commissioner determines that an insurance
33 holding company system exempted from the filing requirements of subsection (a) of this section
34 no longer meets the requirements for an exemption, the insurance holding company system shall
35 file the group capital calculation at the next annual filing date unless given an extension by the
36 lead state commissioner based on reasonable grounds shown. If the lead state commissioner,
37 pursuant to subsection (f) of this section, either grants a discretionary exemption or authorizes a
38 limited group capital filing, the lead state commissioner may require the ultimate controlling
39 person of that insurance holding company system to file an annual group calculation at any time
40 if any of the following apply:
41 (1) Any insurer within the insurance holding company system is in a risk-based
42 capital action level event as set forth in Article 12 of this Chapter or a similar
43 standard for a non-United States insurer.
44 (2) Any insurer within the insurance holding company system meets one or more
45 of the standards of an insurer deemed to be in hazardous financial condition
46 pursuant to the criteria provided in G.S. 58-30-60.
47 (3) Any insurer within the insurance holding company system otherwise exhibits
48 qualities of a troubled insurer as determined by the lead state commissioner
49 based on unique circumstances, including the type and volume of business
50 written, ownership and organizational structure, federal agency requests, and
51 international supervisor requests.
