1 "§ 58-19-27. Liquidity stress test.
2 (a) Participation and Reporting Requirement. – The ultimate controlling person of every
3 insurer subject to registration pursuant to G.S. 58-19-25 shall be included in the NAIC liquidity
4 stress test framework and file a report with the lead state commissioner detailing the results of a
5 specific year's liquidity stress test if either of the following applies:
6 (1) The insurer meets the scope criteria of that data year's NAIC liquidity stress
7 test framework.
8 (2) The insurer did not meet the scope criteria of that data year's liquidity stress
9 test framework, but the lead state commissioner, in consultation with the
10 NAIC Financial Stability Task Force or its successor, nonetheless determines
11 the insurer should be included in the NAIC liquidity stress test framework for
12 that data year. In making this determination, the lead state commissioner shall
13 attempt to avoid the frequent inclusion or exclusion of insurers.
14 (b) The performance of, and filing of the results from, a specific year's liquidity stress
15 test shall comply with (i) the NAIC liquidity stress test framework's instructions and reporting
16 templates for that year and (ii) all lead state commissioners' directives issued in consultation with
17 the NAIC Financial Stability Task Force or its successor.
18 (c) Exemptions. – The lead state commissioner may, in consultation with the NAIC
19 Financial Stability Task Force or its successor, exempt an ultimate controlling person from the
20 reporting requirements of subsection (a) of this section. The lead state commissioner shall
21 consider the intent of regulators to avoid having insurers scoped in and out of the NAIC liquidity
22 stress test framework on a frequent basis when making this determination.
23 "§ 58-19-28. Dissemination prohibited.
24 (a) Unless otherwise provided by law, the making, publishing, disseminating, circulating,
25 or placing before the public, or causing directly or indirectly to be made, published, disseminated,
26 circulated, or placed before the public in a newspaper, magazine, or other publication, or in the
27 form of a notice, circular, pamphlet, letter, or poster, or over any radio or television station or
28 any electronic means of communication available to the public, or in any other way as an
29 advertisement, announcement, or statement containing a representation or statement with regard
30 to the group capital calculation, group capital ratio, the liquidity stress test results, or supporting
31 disclosures for the liquidity stress test of any insurer or any insurer group, or of any component
32 derived in the calculation by any insurer, broker, or other person engaged in any manner in the
33 insurance business is prohibited.
34 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this section, if any materially false statement with
35 respect to the group capital calculation, resulting group capital ratio, an inappropriate comparison
36 of any amount to an insurer's or insurance group's group capital calculation or resulting group
37 capital ratio, liquidity stress test result, supporting disclosures for the liquidity stress test, or an
38 inappropriate comparison of any amount to an insurer's or insurance group's liquidity stress test
39 result, or supporting disclosures is published in any written publication and the insurer is able to
40 demonstrate to the Commissioner with substantial proof the falsity or inappropriateness of the
41 statement, then the insurer may publish announcements in a written publication if the sole
42 purpose of the announcement is to rebut the materially false or inappropriate statement."
43
44 PART II. CONFORMING CHANGES
45 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 58-19-5 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 58-19-5. Definitions.
47 As used in this Article, unless the context requires otherwise, the following terms have the
48 following meanings:
49 …
50 (10a) Group capital calculation. – A report, completed in accordance with the group
51 capital calculation instructions as adopted and amended by the NAIC, used to
Page 4 House Bill 358-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 evaluate the capital adequacy of insurance holding company systems that
2 includes information on the sources of capital within the system, where that
3 capital is located, and sources of risk.
4 (10a)(10b) Group-wide supervisor. – The regulatory official authorized to engage in
5 conducting and coordinating group-wide supervision activities who is
6 determined or acknowledged by the Commissioner under G.S. 58-19-38 to
7 have sufficient significant contacts with the internationally active insurance
8 group.
9 …
10 (12b) Lead state commissioner. – The person responsible for regulating the
11 insurance holding company system as determined by the Commissioner in
12 accordance with the procedures within the Financial Analysis Handbook
13 adopted by the NAIC.
14 (12c) Limited group capital filing. – A simplified version of the group capital
15 calculation, completed in accordance with procedures adopted by the NAIC,
16 where an insurance holding company system only provides a limited amount
17 of data, allowing them to avoid the filing of a full group capital calculation.
18 (12d) Liquidity stress test. – A process simulating extreme market conditions to
19 assess an entity's ability to maintain sufficient liquidity in response to adverse
20 events.
21 (12e) NAIC. – The National Association of Insurance Commissioners.
22 (12f) NAIC liquidity stress test framework. – A publication, adopted and amended
23 by the NAIC in accordance with procedures adopted by the NAIC, which
24 includes a history of the NAIC's development of regulatory liquidity stress
25 testing, the scope criteria applicable for a specific data year, and the liquidity
26 stress test instructions and reporting templates for a specific data year.
27 …
28 (13a) Reciprocal jurisdiction. – As defined in G.S. 58-7-21(b)(4b).
29 (13b) Scope criteria. – Designated exposure bases, detailed in the NAIC liquidity
30 stress test framework along with minimum magnitudes thereof for the
31 specified data year, used to establish a preliminary list of insurers included in
32 the NAIC liquidity stress test framework for that data year.
33 …."
